 and images produced in Istanbul from the close of WWI through the early 1930s, Ekmekcioglu gives voice to the community's most prominent public figures, notably Hayganush Mark, a renowned activist, feminist, and editor of the influential journal Hay Gin. These public figures articulated an Armenianess sustained through gendered differences, and women came to play a central role preserving traditions, memory, and the mother tongue within the home. But even as women were being celebrated for their traditional roles, a strong feminist movement found opportunity for leadership within the community. Ultimately, the book explores this paradox: how someone could be an Armenian and a feminist in post-genocide Turkey when, through its various laws and regulations, the key path for Armenians to maintain their identity was through traditionally gendered roles.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aArmenianszTurkeyxEthnic identityxHistoryy20th century. 0aArmenianszTurkeyxHistoryy20th century. 0aFeminismzTurkeyxHistoryy20th century. 4aArmenians. 4aConstantinople/Istanbul. 4aThird world feminism. 4aTurkey. 4agender. 4ainterwar Europe. 4aminorities in the Middle East. 4aorphans. 4asurvivors. 4athe Armenian genocide. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479719140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804797191423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804797191.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles